<subSubSection pageId="39" pageNumber="340" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1437,505,1970]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1477,1502]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[332,543,1478,1501]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cotaxe" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[332,543,1478,1501]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">Campsurus cotaxe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[554,647,1477,1502]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[554,647,1477,1502]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, known from adults of both sexes, can be distinguished from other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[281,409,1514,1537]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[281,409,1514,1537]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">Campsurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by: 1) sternum IX with straight hind margin (
<figureCitation box="[975,1091,1513,1538]" captionStart="FIGURES 138 – 145" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1925,1948]" captionTargetBox="[283,1282,265,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[277,1285,265,1880]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 138 – 145. C. segnis, holotype male imago: 138, genitalia, v. v.; 139, penes, v. v. Campsurus cotaxe sp. nov.: 140, genitalia, v. v.; 141, pedestal, v. v.; 142, penes, v. v.; 143, penes, l. v.; 144, female sternum VIII with detail of socket. C. amapaensis: 145, partial view of female sternum VIII with detail of socket." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838472/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">Figs. 140</figureCitation>
); 2) pedestal bases distinctly separated in the middle, parastylus conical, subequal in length to main body of pedestal, inner corner also projected but slightly (
<figureCitation box="[305,465,1585,1610]" captionStart="FIGURES 138 – 145" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1925,1948]" captionTargetBox="[283,1282,265,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[277,1285,265,1880]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 138 – 145. C. segnis, holotype male imago: 138, genitalia, v. v.; 139, penes, v. v. Campsurus cotaxe sp. nov.: 140, genitalia, v. v.; 141, pedestal, v. v.; 142, penes, v. v.; 143, penes, l. v.; 144, female sternum VIII with detail of socket. C. amapaensis: 145, partial view of female sternum VIII with detail of socket." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838472/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">Fig. 140–141</figureCitation>
); 3) penes base well developed, main lobe of penes long and cylindrical, curved ventromedially, secondary lobe of penes shorter, cylindrical (
<figureCitation box="[854,1080,1621,1646]" captionStart="FIGURES 138 – 145" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1925,1948]" captionTargetBox="[283,1282,265,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[277,1285,265,1880]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 138 – 145. C. segnis, holotype male imago: 138, genitalia, v. v.; 139, penes, v. v. Campsurus cotaxe sp. nov.: 140, genitalia, v. v.; 141, pedestal, v. v.; 142, penes, v. v.; 143, penes, l. v.; 144, female sternum VIII with detail of socket. C. amapaensis: 145, partial view of female sternum VIII with detail of socket." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838472/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">Figs. 140, 142–143</figureCitation>
); 4) small size (length of male fore wings ca. 
<quantity box="[314,410,1658,1682]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" unit="mm" value="7.5" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="7.0">7–8 mm</quantity>
); 5) female sockets small, anteromedian and V-shaped (
<figureCitation box="[1030,1138,1657,1682]" captionStart="FIGURES 138 – 145" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1925,1948]" captionTargetBox="[283,1282,265,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[277,1285,265,1880]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 138 – 145. C. segnis, holotype male imago: 138, genitalia, v. v.; 139, penes, v. v. Campsurus cotaxe sp. nov.: 140, genitalia, v. v.; 141, pedestal, v. v.; 142, penes, v. v.; 143, penes, l. v.; 144, female sternum VIII with detail of socket. C. amapaensis: 145, partial view of female sternum VIII with detail of socket." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838472/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">Figs. 144</figureCitation>
); 6) egg without polar cap, with amorphous, circular structure on convex side.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="39" pageNumber="340" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="39.[151,1437,505,1970]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,1729,1754]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[343,554,1730,1753]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cotaxe" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[343,554,1730,1753]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">Campsurus cotaxe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[565,658,1729,1754]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[565,658,1729,1754]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Needham &amp; Murphy ." authorityYear="1924" box="[820,926,1730,1753]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="segnis">
<emphasis box="[820,926,1730,1753]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">C. segnis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Traver" authorityYear="1947" box="[988,1098,1729,1754]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ulmeri">
<emphasis box="[988,1098,1729,1754]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">C. ulmeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, sharing the general form of pedestals and penes, especially the long and narrow penes lobes (main and secondary), that are medially and ventrally curved. These morphologically similar species can be distinguished because the base of the penes is well developed in 
<taxonomicName authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[301,407,1838,1861]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cotaxe" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[301,407,1838,1861]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">C. cotaxe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[414,503,1837,1862]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[414,503,1837,1862]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
(bp in 
<figureCitation box="[583,680,1837,1862]" captionStart="FIGURES 138 – 145" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1925,1948]" captionTargetBox="[283,1282,265,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[277,1285,265,1880]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 138 – 145. C. segnis, holotype male imago: 138, genitalia, v. v.; 139, penes, v. v. Campsurus cotaxe sp. nov.: 140, genitalia, v. v.; 141, pedestal, v. v.; 142, penes, v. v.; 143, penes, l. v.; 144, female sternum VIII with detail of socket. C. amapaensis: 145, partial view of female sternum VIII with detail of socket." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838472/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">Fig. 140</figureCitation>
), and the penes lobes (mainly the secondary ones) are basally fused to the penes base (
<figureCitation box="[378,481,1873,1898]" captionStart="FIGURES 138 – 145" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1925,1948]" captionTargetBox="[283,1282,265,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[277,1285,265,1880]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 138 – 145. C. segnis, holotype male imago: 138, genitalia, v. v.; 139, penes, v. v. Campsurus cotaxe sp. nov.: 140, genitalia, v. v.; 141, pedestal, v. v.; 142, penes, v. v.; 143, penes, l. v.; 144, female sternum VIII with detail of socket. C. amapaensis: 145, partial view of female sternum VIII with detail of socket." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838472/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">Fig. 140</figureCitation>
). In the other two species, both penes lobes (main and secondary) form a more independent unit (
<figureCitation box="[358,459,1909,1934]" captionStart="FIGURES 138 – 145" captionStartId="38.[151,264,1925,1948]" captionTargetBox="[283,1282,265,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@38.[277,1285,265,1880]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="FIGURES 138 – 145. C. segnis, holotype male imago: 138, genitalia, v. v.; 139, penes, v. v. Campsurus cotaxe sp. nov.: 140, genitalia, v. v.; 141, pedestal, v. v.; 142, penes, v. v.; 143, penes, l. v.; 144, female sternum VIII with detail of socket. C. amapaensis: 145, partial view of female sternum VIII with detail of socket." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/838472/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">Fig. 138</figureCitation>
). Furthermore, the pedestals are different: the parastylus is shorter, narrowing toward the apex in 
<taxonomicName authority="Molineri &amp; Salles, 2017" authorityName="Molineri &amp; Salles" authorityYear="2017" box="[281,386,1946,1969]" class="Insecta" family="Polymitarcyidae" genus="Campsurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cotaxe" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[281,386,1946,1969]" italics="true" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">C. cotaxe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[393,483,1945,1970]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[393,483,1945,1970]" pageId="39" pageNumber="340">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but it is long and slender from the base in the other two species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
